once i was young, blue and “l’appel du bide” was my favourite word.

then i got to Preikestolen. above Lysefjord, in Norway. 
604 metres high. straightly high. so when you think you have the urge to jump, the breath-taking scene of eternal deep blue water, ice glaciers amongst mountains with somewhat green nature gently waving over crevices, all of those will hold you back.

and i did step back. but i let a character die in my story that way. “l’appel du vide”. that’s it.

There's one thing surprised me when I found Mus�e Michelet here. Yes, it's Jules Michelet - the one who used and defined "Renaissance" for the first time ever in history in his famous work French Revolution History and History of France. But why Vascoeuil, when he was not the owner?

It's because, his greatest love - Mme Dumesnil - was living here. The place is full of correspondences between these two, and none of them was spoken of. Not a name mentioned in his life we studied on textbook, not a place they lived and visited together, not even anything he wrote when he wrote about marriage.

But she was his everything. “Because you have won my confidence and you have inspired me more than anyone else”, after that letter Jules introduced his original conception of the Renaissance. When she died only after 2 years they first met, Jules remained considerably distraught over his irretrievable loss. His words were not those of guilt followed by an analysis, as with Pauline - his first wife, but they were profound and timeless loneliness.

And yet only I found out when I got here, in a lovely sunny afternoon. how many splendid afternoons like this they did enjoy together?
